{{italic title}}
The '''''Taktikon Uspensky''''' or '''''Uspenskij''''' is the conventional name of a mid-9th century [[Greek language|Greek]] list of the civil, military and ecclesiastical offices of the [[Byzantine Empire]] and their precedence at the imperial court. [[Nicolas Oikonomides]] has dated it to 842/843,<ref>Oikonomides (1972), pp. 41ff.</ref> making it the first of a series of such documents (''[[Taktika (disambiguation)|taktika]]'') extant from the 9th and 10th centuries.<ref>Kazhdan (1991), p. 2007</ref> The document is named after the Russian Byzantinist [[Fyodor Uspensky]], who discovered it in the late 19th century in a 12th/13th-century manuscript (''codex Hierosolymitanus gr. 39'') in the library of the [[Eastern Orthodox Patriarchate of Jerusalem]], which also contained a portion of the ''[[Kletorologion]]'' of Philotheos, a later ''taktikon''.<ref>Bury (1911), pp. 10, 12</ref>

== Editions ==
* Russian edition, by F. Uspensky: {{cite journal | title = Византийская табель о рангах |trans-title= Byzantine table of ranks | journal = Известия Русского Археологического Института в Константинополе| year = 1898 | volume = 3 | url = http://www.library.chersonesos.org/showtome.php?tome_code=93&section_code=6 | pages = 98–137}}
* French edition, by N. Oikonomides: {{cite book | title = Les listes de préséance byzantines des IXe et Xe siècles | location = Paris | year = 1972 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=RFdmAAAAMAAJ | pages = 47–63}}

